following courses while in Buenos Aires:     Social Work Practice III   Social Work Research II   Human Behavior III   Field Instruction III (overseen by a Silver faculty member and someone in Buenos Aires)   Elective (TBD)*     *Spanish fluency is not required, but preferred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           FAQ:     Do I need to be fluent in Spanish?   Students do not need to be fluent in order to study in Argentina. However, students will need to demonstrate advanced beginner Spanish by September 2015. A placement test will be used to determine student level for the Spanish for Social Workers course to be taken in Buenos Aires.     What are the electives being offered?   Students will have a choice of two electives: Spanish for Social Workers or Global Mental Health Practice.     Where will my field placement be while studying Buenos Aires?   Students will have their second year field placement with the McSilver Institute. During the fall semester, students will work with McSilver's community-based partners in Argentina. Examples of possible placements include:     Rivadavia Hospital: Students will work alongside social workers in the Emergency Room or other inpatient treatment programs at the oldest public hospital in Buenos Aires (Spanish fluency required).   Sembrando Creatividad: Students will work as part of a multidisciplinary art therapy team promoting the social-emotional development of children ages 6-12. (Beginner to advanced Spanish required).   The Secretariat for Habitat & Inclusion: Students will work on a range of projects from research to program development and evaluation within the official government agency of Buenos Aires whose mission is to promote sustainable urbanization and social inclusion. (Beginner to advanced Spanish required).     Upon returning to New York, students will complete their second year field placement with the McSilver Institute. During the fall semester, students will work with McSilver's community-based partners in Argentina. In the spring, students will work with McSilver either in one of their direct-service programs or on one of their research initiatives. Some students will have the opportunity to continue working on a project started in Buenos Aires during the fall semester.     Does my financial aid cover the semester abroad?   If you are currently receiving financial aid, it will apply to the semester abroad. Please contact the Office of Financial Aid with any questions pertaining to your personal financial aid award package for 2015-2016.        Are there any scholarships available?   Scholarship opportunities are being investigated. Information is forthcoming.      Where will I live while in Buenos Aires?   Students will be able to arrange for their own housing for the semester. A list of vetted apartment rental companies will be provided. Program staff members are available to assist with finding appropriate housing.     How do I apply for the semester abroad in Buenos Aires?   Interested students should complete the online application available on this page. After the application has been reviewed, you will be contacted for a brief in-person interview. The application deadline is February 1, 2015. The online application will be available shortly.       How many students will be accepted into the program?   12 to 15 students will be accepted.     I have questions not listed here, how can I receive more information?   You should plan to attend an information session on any of the following dates: Tuesday, November 12 or Wednesday, November 13. These sessions will take place in room 207 from 3:55 - 4:55 pm. You can also contact Gisselle Pardo, LCSW with any questions.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 The application for this program is now closed. following courses while in Buenos Aires:     Social Work Practice III   Social Work Research II   Human Behavior III   Field Instruction III (overseen by a Silver faculty member and someone in Buenos Aires)   Elective (TBD)*     *Spanish fluency is not required, but preferred.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       FAQ:     Do I need to be fluent in Spanish?   Students do not need to be fluent in order to study in Argentina. However, students will need to demonstrate advanced beginner Spanish by September 2015. A placement test will be used to determine student level for the Spanish for Social Workers course to be taken in Buenos Aires.     What are the electives being offered?   Students will have a choice of two electives: Spanish for Social Workers or Global Mental Health Practice.     Where will my field placement be while studying Buenos Aires?   Students will have their second year field placement with the McSilver Institute. During the fall semester, students will work with McSilver's community-based partners in Argentina. Examples of possible placements include:     Rivadavia Hospital: Students will work alongside social workers in the Emergency Room or other inpatient treatment programs at the oldest public hospital in Buenos Aires (Spanish fluency required).   Sembrando Creatividad: Students will work as part of a multidisciplinary art therapy team promoting the social-emotional development of children ages 6-12. (Beginner to advanced Spanish required).   The Secretariat for Habitat & Inclusion: Students will work on a range of projects from research to program development and evaluation within the official government agency of Buenos Aires whose mission is to promote sustainable urbanization and social inclusion. (Beginner to advanced Spanish required).     Upon returning to New York, students will complete their second year field placement with the McSilver Institute. During the fall semester, students will work with McSilver's community-based partners in Argentina. In the spring, students will work with McSilver either in one of their direct-service programs or on one of their research initiatives. Some students will have the opportunity to continue working on a project started in Buenos Aires during the fall semester.     Does my financial aid cover the semester abroad?   If you are currently receiving financial aid, it will apply to the semester abroad. Please contact the Office of Financial Aid with any questions pertaining to your personal financial aid award package for 2015-2016.        Are there any scholarships available?   Scholarship opportunities are being investigated. Information is forthcoming.      Where will I live while in Buenos Aires?   Students will be able to arrange for their own housing for the semester. A list of vetted apartment rental companies will be provided. Program staff members are available to assist with finding appropriate housing.     How do I apply for the semester abroad in Buenos Aires?   Interested students should complete the online application available on this page. After the application has been reviewed, you will be contacted for a brief in-person interview. The application deadline is February 1, 2015. The online application will be available shortly.       How many students will be accepted into the program?   12 to 15 students will be accepted.     I have questions not listed here, how can I receive more information?   You should plan to attend an information session on any of the following dates: Tuesday, November 12 or Wednesday, November 13. These sessions will take place in room 207 from 3:55 - 4:55 pm. You can also contact Gisselle Pardo, LCSW with any questions. Where can I find general information about NYU’s MS in Data Science program?   Navigate to the web site for the Center for Data Science at NYU (cds.nyu.edu) and follow the links to Programs and Admissions .   Is the degree offered online?   No, presently we do not have an online program.   Will most of the classes be offered at night?   All of the required courses are offered on or after 5 p.m. Elective courses are offered both before and after 5 p.m.   May I apply for admission in the spring?   No. We will not be accepting new students for the spring. However, our applications for Fall 2014 will be opening in September.   May I apply for more than one graduate degree at NYU?   That depends on how your multiple applications are split up over the NYU schools. You can apply concurrently to as many NYU schools as you wish. Some schools allow you to apply to multiple programs. However, the MS in Data Science is part of the Graduate School of Arts and Science, which permits only one application at a time.   May I take courses without applying for a degree?   Yes. Non-degree students can be admitted. Follow the link to the application form for more information. There is a limit on the number of such courses you can take without getting admitted to a degree program.   I’m currently a student at NYU. How can I apply for the MS in Data Science?   Students enrolled in any other NYU graduate program must submit a new application.   NYU students enrolled in a Courant graduate degree cannot apply for a transfer following the same procedures that apply to transfers into the MS in Information Systems.   Do I have enough programming experience?   See the admission requirements for the experience needed.   Which programming languages will be used in each course?   Programming languages are decided by the professor of each course. For the 2013-2014 year, students mostly used Python.   Will some courses be cross-listed with other departments within NYU?   All of the required courses for the MS in Data Science are available to all students at NYU.   Which courses are required for an MS in Data Science?   The course curriculum for an MS in Data Science can be found on the  NYU Center for Data Science website .   What sort of classes will be offered as electives?   Generally speaking any MS or higher-level course at NYU on data science-related disciplines (such as optimization, probability, statistics) or data science related domains (such as biology, economics, physics, business, sociology, urban science) are eligible. We will publish a definitive list. In addition, students with an interest in courses not on the list may apply to the faculty member responsible for the degree for permission on a case-by-case basis. The design of the program has 6 electives and 6 required courses so that students can pursue their interests in data science disciplines or in data science domains.   You can look at suggested and pre-approved electives courses on the website.   Will CPT or OPT be offered?   CPT is “curricular practical training,” a program which allows international students to obtain paid internships for credit during the first year of the degree. We will not offer CPT.   OPT is “optional practical training,” a program which allows international students to obtain paid internships without credit either during or after the degree. We are STEM eligible and thus offer OPT for 29 months.   Is the program available to full-time employees and/or part-time students?   Both full-time and part-time students are welcomed.   How big is the current class?   The inaugural Fall 2013 class consists of 31 students. We plan to admit more students for Fall 2014.   Are international students accepted?   NYU seeks talented students from every corner of the globe.   Who will be teaching?   Instructors for required courses will be drawn from across all the schools of NYU, though initially primarily from the Courant faculty (cs.nyu.edu and math.nyu.edu). Foster Provost from the Stern School of Business will teach DS-GA-1001 Intro to Data Science in the Fall 2013 semester.   Is there a PhD program in Data Science?   Not yet.   How much does the program cost?   Tuition and fees for the current Academic Year can be found here: http://www.nyu.edu/bursar/tuition.fees/rate13/gradgsas.html .  Tuition and fees for 2013-2014 will be posted on the bursar’s web page when they are available. The bursar expects to finalize tuition and fees in mid May.   Does NYU offer financial aid and/or scholarships?   See http://cds.nyu.edu/academics/ms-in-data-science/ .   What are the prerequisites for admission to this program?   See http://cds.nyu.edu/academics/admission-requirements/   Do I need to take the GRE or GMAT to apply?  If so, what scores will be accepted?   Yes, each applicant must submit his or her GRE or GMAT score.  If you have not yet  taken either the GRE or GMAT exam, visit their websites to find more information on  exam dates and registration.   What is the minimum cutoff for GRE, GMAT, and TOEFL?   Many factors are taken into account in considering by the admissions committee. There are no minimum cutoff criteria for standardized tests.   How much linear algebra do I need to have taken?   One undergraduate course is sufficient.   What is the application deadline?   See  http://cds.nyu.edu/apply/.   Are there different requirements for international students?   For more information for  international students interested in the MS in Data Science program, please visit the NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science website .   I am very interested in the Data Science program, but I do not have a strong background in math.  Can I still apply?   A strong background in math is required (see http://cds.nyu.edu/academics/admission-requirements/ for details). However, NYU has other Master’s programs with significant data science content and Master’s programs that allow students to take data science courses as electives. See http://datascience.nyu.edu/academics/programs/   Are there any internships or volunteer opportunities in NYU Data Science?   Not at this time, but the program is in the process of building relationships with business partners in the New York area to develop internship opportunities for students.   How can I apply for an administrative position in the NYU Data Science department?   Administrative positions available in Data Science will be posted here:   http://www.nyu.edu/about/working-at-nyu.html .   Are Teaching Assistant (TA) or Research Assistant (RA) positions available for students enrolled in the program?   We don’t use the term “Teaching Assistant” but we do sometimes have grading and tutoring positions qualified students. Hiring for these positions is done by the Mathematics and Computer Science departments each semester. Research assistantships are not available to master’s students.     For further details about funding suggestions, please see  http://gsas.nyu.edu/page/grad. financialaid       What about other types of jobs?     Browse available part-time and internship positions on the NYU Wasserman Center for Career Services website:  http://www.nyu.edu/ careerdevelopment/ .  The full-time NYU positions are listed here:  http://www.nyu.edu/ about/working-at-nyu/apply- for-jobs.html , although full-time students’ schedules may not accommodate full-time work as well.   Is financial aid available?   See http://gsas.nyu.edu/page/grad. financialaid   How many courses should I plan to take each semester?   The full-time program is designed to be 4 semesters. The suggested workload is 3 3-credit courses per semester resulting in 9 credits per semester.   If you are an international student, you normally need to take 12 credits per semester so that the immigration authorities classify you as a full-time student. However, if you enroll for 3 courses and have a student visa, we will code you in our system as having full-time equivalency, which will satisfy the immigration authorities.   We don’t suggest attempting more than 3 courses per semester, as most courses have both significant mathematical content and programming assignments.   We list a 3-semester option on this website which shows 5 courses in the first semester. The purpose of that listing is to satisfy a New York State requirement that makes some New York State students eligible for a particular scholarship. We don’t expect any students to actually register for that many classes.   I’ve enrolled. When should I sign up for courses?   As soon as possible. We have reserved seats in the required courses for MS in Data Science students. However, seats in the elective courses are not reserved and are allocated on a first-come, first-served basis. NYU students have had the ability to enroll in classes since April 22nd.   Can I work full-time while taking classes?   The suggested full-time program is 9 credits per semester. Because of the heavy workload, 9 credits will equal out to about 40 hours of work per week. Students should be able to work jobs while taking classes, but due to the amount of work required for the program, we suggest taking 6 credits per semester, if you would like to work also.   What is the Center for Data Science School Code for the GRE, the TOEFL, and the GMAT?   The school code for GRE and TOEFLs is 2596.  The school code for GMAT is 5TF-5G-76.
